<p>Use strong, simple verbs without adverbs. For instance, rather than â€œran quickly,â€ try â€œsprinted.â€ Note that I said â€œsimpleâ€ verbs. If your point is that someone is slowly walking with no plan to be anywhere, then â€œwanderedâ€ is probably best, but â€œwalked slowly with no goal in mindâ€ is better than â€œperambulated,â€ even though the latter is a fun word.</p>

<p>Why? Whatâ€™s wrong with â€œperambulatedâ€ and whatâ€™s so great about simple, strong verbs? Your goal, when writing, should be to plant an image in the readerâ€™s head. Do whatever best serves that goal. Most readers will get a sharper image with â€œsprintedâ€ than â€œran quickly,â€ and most will also find it easier to imagine â€œwanderingâ€ (or â€œwalking slowly with no goal in mindâ€) than â€œperambulating,â€ which they may even have to look up in a dictionary.</p>

<p>A thesaurus is your best friend (and nowadays heâ€™s free online!). If you have in mind a certain kind of fast running, but all you can think of is â€œrun,â€ the thesaurus will suggest bound, break, canter, dart, dash, drop, escape, fall, flight, gallop, jog, race, rush, scamper, scuttle, spring, sprint, spurt, tear, and whisk.</p>

<p>Donâ€™t make it a pain in the ass to use the thesaurus. I recommend having thesaurus.com open in another window â€“ not another tab â€“ so that you never feel the urge to say, â€œWell, I guess I should look this up in the thesaurus, butâ€¦â€</p>

